# Living glossary for the `proposals` project — {term, plain, why}. The concept-gap quiz draws on this.
{"term": "proposal", "plain": "a frozen, written-once snapshot of a whole plan — one research bet captured at a moment", "why": "it's the new atomic unit this feature introduces; today there is only a single mutable plan"}
{"term": "plan", "plain": "the ordered list of decisions that defines a project (research/plan.<name>.jsonl)", "why": "today it's a singleton that gets overwritten; a proposal is a frozen copy of one"}
{"term": "snapshot", "plain": "a point-in-time copy that is never edited again, only superseded", "why": "the mechanism that turns the mutable plan into an append-only history"}
{"term": "append-only", "plain": "you only ever add records; nothing is deleted or rewritten", "why": "failed bets must stay on the record — that record is the institutional memory trainlint exists to keep"}
{"term": "active-project", "plain": "the .active-project file holding the ONE project name trainlint currently operates on", "why": "the feature retires its privilege — proposals are flat with no single active one"}
{"term": "lifecycle status", "plain": "a plan-LEVEL state (draft/active/accepted/superseded/abandoned), separate from per-decision open/decided/verified", "why": "a proposal needs its own state independent of whether its individual decisions are settled"}
{"term": "lineage", "plain": "the chain of which proposal supersedes which", "why": "append-only history is only navigable if each bet points at what it replaced"}
{"term": "doorman", "plain": "the online hook layer that locates a live action on the plan and routes/escalates by the decision's state", "why": "it keys off the single active project today, so the flat model forces a rethink of its target"}
{"term": "compass", "plain": "the per-turn ambient reminder that keeps the goal + main thread + anti-priors in view", "why": "like the doorman, it assumes one active plan and must be retargeted"}
